IoC Overview: How Spring Handles Object Management :

IoC (Inversion of Control) is a core principle in Spring. It means the control of creating
and managing objects (beans) is transferred from your code to the Spring container. Instead
of you instantiating classes with new, Spring creates, configures, and manages the lifecycle
of objects for you.

How it works:

You define beans (Java objects) and their dependencies.
Spring reads this configuration (via annotations or XML).
Spring creates the beans and injects dependencies where needed.
Benefits:

Loose coupling between components.
Easier testing and maintenance.
Centralized configuration.

Example:

@Component
public class UserService {
    // Spring will inject UserRepository here
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;
}
Here, you don’t create UserService or UserRepository manually—Spring does it for you.

